The dataset was created for the DARPA Intrusion Detection Evaluation Program, prepared and managed by MIT Lincoln Laboratory. The data was collected ovar nine weeks and consist of raw rcpdump traffic in a local area network (LAN) that simulates the environment of a typical US Air Forca LAN. Some network attacks were deliberetaly carried out during the recording period.

#Differentiating between nominal, binary and numeric features

#root shell is marked as a continuous feature in the kddcup.names
#file, but ut us supposed to be a binary feature according to the data set documentation

col_names = np.array(header_names)

nominal_idx = [1,2,3]
binary_idx = [6, 11,13,14,20, 21]
numeric_idx = list(set(range(41)).difference(nominal_idx).difference(binary_idx))

nominal_cols = col_names[nominal_idx].tolist()
binary_cols = col_names[binary_idx].tolist()
numeric_cols = col_names[numeric_idx].tolist()

#training_attack_types.txt maps each of the 22 different attacks to 1 of 4 catefories
#file obrained from http://kdd.ics.udi.edu/databases/kddcup99/training_attack_types
category = defaultdict(list)
category['benign'].append('normal')

with open(r'/home/mateusz/Documents/nsl-kdd/training_attack_types.txt', mode = 'r', encoding = 'utf-8-sig') as f:
    for line in f.readlines():
        print(line.strip().split(' '))
        attack, cat = line.strip().split(' ')
        category[cat].append(attack)

attack_mapping = dict((v,k) for k in category for v in category[k])

In our data we have 41 attack types specified, that falls into 5 classes: -benign, probe - brute-force probing attacks,r2l- unauthorized accesses from remot service, u2r - privilage escalation attempts, dos - denial of service

In [8]:
train_df = pd.read_csv(train_file, names=header_names)
train_df['attack_category'] = train_df['attack_type'] \
                                .map(lambda x: attack_mapping[x])
train_df.drop(['success_pred'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    
test_df = pd.read_csv(test_file, names=header_names)
test_df['attack_category'] = test_df['attack_type'] \
                                .map(lambda x: attack_mapping[x])
test_df.drop(['success_pred'], axis=1, inplace=True)

It's worth noting that there are more types of vulnerabilities in test set than in a train set. We could potentially put the vulnerabilities with smaller number of occurences into a seperate category, say, other or just ignore them. it's a common practice to mitigate overfitting, avoid domination of one class.

The data is tremendously imbalanced and it's necessary to balance out the data set in order to prevent the classifier from an undesireble bias by learning more about 'benign' and 'dos' classes, than 'u2r' and 'r2l' classes, since there are more occurences in the data of those.

The data was in structured and clean (no NULLs), with one exception where value 2 was assigned to one of the binary features 'su_attempted'.

The distribution of rach feature vary widely, which will affect our results if we use any distance-based methods for classification. For instance, the mean of src_bytes is larger then the mean of num_failed_logins by seven orders of magnitude, and its standard deviation is larger by eigt orders of magnitude. Without performing feature value standardization/normalization, the src_bytes feature would dominate, causing the model to miss out on potentially important information in the num_failed_logins feature.

from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler

mean_class_size = int(pd.Series(train_Y).value_counts().sum()/5)

ratio = {'benign': mean_class_size,
         'dos': mean_class_size,
         'probe': mean_class_size,
         'r2l': mean_class_size,
         'u2r': mean_class_size
    
}
rus =RandomUnderSampler(ratio=ratio, random_state=0, replacement=True)
train_x_rus, train_Y_rus = rus.fit_sample(train_x_sm, train_Y_sm)
print(pd.Series(train_Y_rus).value_counts())

r2l       25194

Attempting Unsupervised Learning

Clustering is a class of methods used in unsupervised learning. It's a technique that group similar data samples together, by definition of similarity. Each group of similar points is called a cluster and each cluster represents the learned model of a category. In our dataset we apply k-means clustering to find a pattern in unlabeled datapoints. We know that in our dataset contain five categories of samples, so we will choose the k-means clustering algorithm for the test with k = 5. K-means works only with continous data, hence we use only continious features in our data.

We applied PCA for dimensionality reduction in order to plot the relation between the vulnerabilities in 2D. We ignore labels and perform unsupervised learning to cluster datapoints by their similarities. The result is shown in the plot below.

It seems like the last cluster didn't get any membership of any of the test data points. We can observe significant differences in the clusters formed by k-means and the grond truth clusters. The algorithm performs well in grouping certain sections of the data together, but it fails to group clusters of the dos label and wrongly classifies a large section of "benign" trafic as attack traffic. None of the clusters have lables associated with them, thus evaluating results of clusters is not as simple as just comparing the predicted and expected labels. In the plot above, it's seen that there is a discrepancy between expected and predicted classes. The sense of how reliable the algorithm is, gives us metrics such as Completeness, Homogeneity and V-measure.

A cluster is complete (has completeness score 1) if all data points belonging to the same class are clustered together. A cluster is homogoneous ( has homogeneity score 1) if all data points that are clustered together bolong tho the same class. The V-measure is a harmonic mean of homogeneity and completeness.

Attribute Ratio feature selection is a method for algorithmically assigning the highest scores to the features that provide the best model. From all the features algorithms narrows down to 72 features (AR >= 0.1) that are the most infirmative and ranks them in decreasing order.

def binary_AR(df, col):
    series_zero = train_df[train_df[col] == 0].groupby('attack_category').size()
    series_one = train_df[train_df[col] == 1].groupby('attack_category').size()
    return max(series_one/series_zero)

Looking at the above table, we must consider how we want to deal with each cluster. Clusters 2 and 6 have a very clear majority of attack traffic, clusters 3 and 7 seem to contain only low level of noise, the rest of clusters are quite mixed.

Ensembling strategy

  1. For clusters that have an aggregate size of fewer than 200 samples, we consider them outliers and assign them the attack label.

  2. For clusters with more than 95% of samples belonging to a single class, (either attack or benign) we assign the dominant label to the entire cluster.

  3. For each of the remaining clusters, we train a separate random forest classifier

    According to this strategy clusters 3 and 7 will be considered "noise" and be assigned the attack label. Clusters 2 and 6 both have more than 99% lf the traffic classified as attacks so that label propagates the entire class. We'll train decision tree classifiers for each of clusters 0,1, 4 and 5. We evaluate our method by first running the test samples through the k-means model to obtain the test clusters. Then, all the test samples assigned to cluster 2, 3, 6 and 7 will immediatly be labeled as attack. Test samples assigned to cluster 0 will be put through the decision tree classifiers train on cluster 0 from the training set, and so on.

If we compare the cross table of the testing data given above with the cross tabulation of the training data, we see that the biggest discrepancies between the attack/benign distributions (where 1 is attacj and 0 benign) within a sigle cluster come form cluster 0.
